Free Speech, the Government, and Scale
--------------------------------------

Speaking of free speech, last week from the Wall Street Journal ( https://w=
ww.wsj.com/articles/judge-rules-biden-administration-likely-trampled-on-fre=
e-speech-on-social-media-29334362 ) :

A federal judge issued a broad preliminary injunction limiting the federal =
government from communicating with social-media companies about online cont=
ent, ruling that Biden administration officials=E2=80=99 policing of social=
-media posts likely violated the First Amendment.

In a 155-page ruling issued Tuesday, U.S. District Judge Terry Doughty of L=
ouisiana barred White House officials and multiple federal agencies from co=
ntacting social-media companies with the purpose of suppressing political v=
iews and other speech normally protected from government censorship. The ju=
dge=E2=80=99s injunction came in a lawsuit led by the Republican attorneys =
general of Missouri and Louisiana who alleged that the Biden administration=
 fostered a sprawling =E2=80=9Cfederal censorship enterprise=E2=80=9D in it=
s effort to stamp out what it viewed as rampant disinformation circulating =
on social media. The government, the lawsuit claimed, pressured social-medi=
a platforms to scrub away disfavored views about Covid-19 health policies, =
the origins of the pandemic, the Hunter Biden laptop story, election securi=
ty and other divisive topics.

I=E2=80=99m not going to get into the actual ruling in this Update, but rat=
her want to highlight three responses that stood out to me, and in conjunct=
ion say something interesting.

First, Mike Masnick has a post at Techdirt ( https://www.techdirt.com/2023/=
07/06/the-good-the-bad-and-the-incredibly-ugly-in-the-court-ruling-regardin=
g-government-contacts-with-social-media/ ) examining =E2=80=9CThe Good, The=
 Bad, and the Incredibly Ugly=E2=80=9D aspects of the ruling; to take a sec=
tion from each (and to be clear, I=E2=80=99m using Masnick=E2=80=99s labels=
 here):

There are legitimate concerns about government intrusions into private comp=
anies and their 1st Amendment protected decisions=E2=80=A6There were some e=
xamples in the lawsuit that did seem likely to cross the line, including ha=
ving officials in the White House complaining about certain tweets and even=
 saying =E2=80=9Cwondering if we can get moving on the process of having it=
 removed ASAP.=E2=80=9D That=E2=80=99s definitely inappropriate. Most of th=
e worst emails seemed to come from one guy, Rob Flaherty, the former =E2=80=
=9CDirector of Digital Strategy,=E2=80=9D who seemed to believe his job in =
the White House made it fine for him to be a total jackass to the companies=
, constantly berating them for moderation choices he disliked=E2=80=A6

Also, the ruling highlights that lawmakers threatening to revoke or modify =
Section 230 as part of the process of working the refs at these social medi=
a companies is a form of retaliation. This is a surprising finding, but a g=
ood one. We=E2=80=99ve highlighted in the past that politicians threatening=
 to punish companies with regulatory changes in response to speech should b=
e seen as a 1st Amendment violation, and had people yell at us (on both sid=
es) about that. But here, Judge Doughty agrees, and highlights 230 reform a=
s an example.

From Masnick=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9CBad=E2=80=9D section:

Doughty seems incredibly willing to include perfectly reasonable conversati=
ons about how to respond to actually problematic content as =E2=80=9Ccensor=
ship=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Ccoercion,=E2=80=9D despite there being little ev=
idence of either in many cases (again, in some cases, it does appear that s=
ome folks in the administration crossed the line). For example, it=E2=80=99=
s public information (as we=E2=80=99ve discussed) that various parts of the=
 government would meet with social media not for =E2=80=9Ccensorship=E2=80=
=9D but to share information, such as about foreign trolls seeking to disru=
pt elections with false information, or about particular dangers. These mee=
tings were not about censorship, but just making everyone aware of what was=
 going on. But conspiracy-minded folks have turned those meetings into some=
thing they most definitely are not.

Yet Doughty assumes all these meetings are nefarious. In doing so, Doughty =
often fails to distinguish perfectly reasonable speech by government actors=
 that is not about suppressing speech, but rather debunking or countering f=
alse information =E2=80=94 which is traditional counterspeech. Now, again, =
when government actors are doing it, their speech is actually less protecte=
d (Posner=E2=80=99s ruling in the Dart case details this point), but so lon=
g as their speech is not focused on silencing other speech, it=E2=80=99s pe=
rfectly reasonable.

From Masnick=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9CUgly=E2=80=9D section:

Judge Doughty seems to believe every nonsense conspiracy around regarding t=
he culture war and false claims of social media deliberately stifling =E2=
=80=9Cconservatives.=E2=80=9D This is despite multiple studies showing that=
 they actually bent over backwards to allow conservatives to regularly brea=
k the rules to avoid claims of bias=E2=80=A6

The court is only aware of such speech being moderated because that=E2=80=
=99s all the plaintiffs in this case highlighted (often through exaggeratio=
n). Second, many of the contested actions happened under the Trump administ=
ration, and it would make no sense that a Republican administration would b=
e seeking to suppress =E2=80=9Cconservative=E2=80=9D speech. Third, the who=
le issue is that the companies were choosing to hold back dangerous false i=
nformation that they feared would lead to real world harms. If it was true =
that such speech came more frequently from so-called =E2=80=9Cconservatives=
,=E2=80=9D that=E2=80=99s on them. Not the government.

Second, Patrick McKenzie has a Twitter thread ( https://twitter.com/patio11=
/status/1676592554211459072 ) that makes what I think is an essential obser=
vation in response to a story of one specific misguided takedown:

( https://twitter.com/patio11/status/1676583713478676480?ref_src=3Dtwsrc%5E=
tfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed%7Ctwterm%5E1676583713478676480%7Ctwgr%5E507ce0f05=
6179c5b7d0da0888aa700e36bfb003b%7Ctwcon%5Es1_&ref_url=3Dhttp%3A%2F%2Fchrome=
-headless.local%3A9222%2Fatomic )

McKenzie=E2=80=99s argument is that the reality of moderation is not about =
taking measured decisions over each piece of content, but rather producing =
scalable systems; if that scalable system assumes that government feedback =
is valid and actionable, then the practical effect is government censorship=
, even if the vast majority of feedback is not combined with the sort of th=
reats that Masnick noted. In other words, McKenzie is making the case that =
distinguishing between =E2=80=9Cthe good, the bad, and the ugly=E2=80=9D is=
 fine in theory, but in practice =E2=80=94 at scale =E2=80=94 it=E2=80=99s =
all indistinguishable.

Third, this paragraph from the New York Times story ( https://www.nytimes.c=
om/2023/07/05/us/politics/social-media-ruling-government.html ) about the c=
ase was remarkable:

The case was brought by two Republican attorneys general and five individua=
ls who campaigned against masks, argued that vaccines did not work, opposed=
 lockdowns and pushed drugs that medical experts denounced as ineffective, =
like ivermectin and hydroxychloroquine. And it is being overseen by Judge T=
erry A. Doughty, who was appointed by President Donald J. Trump and has pre=
viously expressed little skepticism about debunked claims from vaccine skep=
tics. In one previous case, Judge Doughty accepted as fact the claim that =
=E2=80=9CCovid-19 vaccines do not prevent transmission of the disease.=E2=
=80=9D

Uhm, Covid-19 vaccines do not prevent transmission of the disease! That=E2=
=80=99s pretty widely accepted at this point =E2=80=94 at least everywhere =
outside of the New York Times newsroom =E2=80=94 which makes it very odd th=
at this is cited as a reason why the judge is given to conspiracy theories.=
 Granted, this was a matter of dispute at one point, but the way that dispu=
te was deployed at scale was to censor a claim that turned out to be true!

The reason I bring up these stories actually comes back to that email: ther=
e are some issues, like free speech, that do come down to principle. My cor=
respondent is upset that I haven=E2=80=99t changed my views on free speech,=
 and he=E2=80=99s right, I haven=E2=80=99t. I support it. Moreover, I suppo=
rt it with the knowledge that this support, when manifested through the blu=
nt instrument of government policy or big tech moderation, means more misin=
formation than there might be otherwise.

My personal belief is that it is impossible =E2=80=94 especially at scale =
=E2=80=94 to get every call right, so I would rather default to more inform=
ation rather than less, because the harms of suppressing the truth are sign=
ificant as well. To use the COVID example, if we had collectively accepted =
that everyone was going to get COVID despite the vaccine, might we have mad=
e different decisions around things like in-person schooling, potentially a=
voiding a devastating decline in test scores ( https://www.nytimes.com/2023=
/06/21/us/naep-test-results-education.html ) amongst kids, particularly tho=
se in disadvantaged circumstances? That is a very real cost that will last =
decades that stems from suppressing the truth, even if the motivation was t=
o suppress misinformation.

I recognize that different people set these priorities differently, or have=
 more faith than I do in the agility and capability of governments and larg=
e companies operated at scale to know the truth and only moderate what is m=
isinformation, and that=E2=80=99s good. Masnick and I, to take one pertinen=
t example, have had a longstanding back-and-forth, both privately and via o=
ur websites, about these very issues.

Moreover, I would say the same thing about the antitrust debate as well: be=
yond the specifics of the Microsoft-Activision case, there are real questio=
ns about whether one=E2=80=99s primary concern is limiting innovation and c=
lear benefits to consumers in the short term, versus big company dominance =
and potential harm in the long run. I do tend towards the former, because I=
=E2=80=99m just not that confident in my ability to know exactly how produc=
ts or markets will play out over decades, but I respect those who have the =
opposite point of view.

What is useful, though, and what makes all of this work, is assuming the go=
od intentions and honest argument of those you disagree with, absent clear =
evidence to the contrary, and, I would argue, a commitment to a system that=
 gives space for views you disagree with. This is obviously most pressing w=
hen it comes to government censorship or tech company moderation, but it ap=
plies on a smaller scale to the means of debate as well.

